<scopecontent>
<p>The Slaves Executed records series, 1781-1864, are housed in 4 boxes and contain case files relating to the condemnation of a slave (or multiple slaves) for capital crimes committed (such as arson, burglary, murder, and rape). The series contains affidavits, correspondence, court records, death warrants, power of attorneys, receipts, sheriff certificates, valuations, and wills.  The cases are identified by the slave owner's name and the date on which the Auditor of Public Accounts paid the owner for his or her loss of the slave(s). The files sometimes include detailed court records about the crime in question, though in many cases the file contains only the valuation and receipt from the Auditor's Office.  Also often included are statements from the sheriff certifying that the execution took place. </p>
<p>Of note are files related to slaves condemned for their involvement in the insurrections led by Gabriel Prosser (1800) and Nat Turner (1831). For Gabriel's Rebellion the slaves executed include: John (slave owner Mary Jones of Hanover County); Charles (slave owner Rogery Gregory of Henrico County); Billy, Frank, Gabriel, Martin, Peter, Solomon, and Tom (slave owner Thomas Henry Prosser of Henrico County); Isaac and Isham (slave owner William Burton of Henrico County); Will (slave owner John Mosby of Henrico County); Micheal alias Mike (slave owner Judity Owen of Henrico County); Ned (slave owner Ann Parsons Henrico County); Jupiter (slave owner Nathaniel Wilkinson of Henrico County); Sawney (slave owner William Lewis of Henrico County); Gilbert and William (slave owner William Young of Henrico County); George (slave owner Jacob Smith estate); Sam alias Sam Byrd (slave owner Jane Clarke of Henrico County); Isaac (slave owner of James Allen of Henrico County); Sam alias Sam Graham (slave owner Paul Graham of Hanover County); Michael (slave owner Thomas Goode of Chesterfield County); and Saddie (slave owner John Williamson of Henrico County). </p>
<p>For Nat Turner's Rebellion the slaves executed include: Ben (slave owner estate of Benjamin Blunt of Southampton County); Moses (slave of Thomas Barrow of Southampton County); Moses (slave owner Putnam Moore estate of Southampton County); Lucy (slave owner John T. Barrow of Southampton County); Daniel (slave owner Richard Porter of Southampton County); Sam (slave owner Peter Edwards of Southampton County); Joe (slave of John C. Turner of Southampton County); Nat (slave of Edmund Turner estate); Jack (slave of William Reese of Southampton County); and Nelson (slave owner Jacob Williams of Southampton County).</p>
</scopecontent>
